What are some of your hacks to retain more information from a book you're reading?

I've started underlining important sentences and plan on skimming the book after I finish it to reread those.
That's a good approach too, though it's more short-term. Underlining has the benefit that you can come back to it months or even years later and refresh the info really fast.
So you just sort of memorize everything? What if you read many books?
Oh, that's an interesting approach! Does it work in terms of remembering the contents better?
I'm so lazy when it comes to writing. Need to form that habit more

I have made a habit out of reading in distraction-free environments, but I somehow haven't found the motivation to start writing notes. Maybe that's why I was bad at school - wasn't using the right system to learn. Thanks for the input!

Should risk-minimizing mechanisms like clawback, streams, multisigs be used in all cases of grants? 

We have an average Joe asking for $100k, and we also have Vitalik asking for $100k.

Should both have the same treatment in regards to the execution of the grant, given both proposals are equally good?
It occured to me that long-term direction is difficult to find in a DAO because it's governed both by users and builders at the same time, the incentives of which are not necessarily always aligned.
